From: Refracta user
Date: 2026-06-29
Subject: [PATCH v7] btrfs layout learning + RAM swap + hibernation + EFI fixes

This patch adds btrfs filesystem support to both the GUI (yad) and CLI
versions of refractainstaller, makes the installer LEARN the btrfs subvolume
layout from the disk, sizes swap to RAM and configures hibernation, fixes EFI
partition mounting and grub installation, and mirrors the installer log to the
target disk.

Filesystem options added:

  1. "btrfs (single partition)" - formats the root partition as btrfs
     without subvolumes. The top-level volume (subvolid=5) is mounted as /.

  2. "btrfs (with subvolumes)" - formats as btrfs, creates a set of
     subvolumes, mounts each at its mountpoint before rsync, and writes
     multiple fstab entries (all sharing one UUID with subvol= options).

Learning the layout from the disk:

  The disk-setup script writes a manifest at the btrfs top level (subvolid=5),
  ".refracta-btrfs-layout", with one TAB-separated "<subvolume><TAB><mountpoint>"
  line per subvolume. load_btrfs_layout() reads it (authoritative), or else
  discovers existing subvolumes via `btrfs subvolume list` and guesses
  mountpoints by convention (btrfs_guess_mount). Entries are sorted by
  mountpoint depth so parents mount before children, and the root subvolume
  (whichever maps to "/") is derived rather than assumed to be "@rootfs".

Swapfile (RAM-sized everywhere, NoCoW on btrfs):

  The swapfile is sized to match the target's RAM (rounded up to a whole GiB),
  auto-detected from /proc/meminfo at install time, for EVERY filesystem -
  instead of the stock 256 MiB default (which rounds to 0 GiB in `free -g`).
  It falls back to the configured size if RAM can't be read. On btrfs the
  swapfile is additionally made NoCoW (chattr +C on an empty file before
  writing); when the layout has a dedicated @swap subvolume the swapfile is
  created inside it (e.g. /swap/swapfile). chmod precedes mkswap.

Hibernation (resume from swap), all scenarios:

  configure_resume() sets the installed system up to resume from hibernation
  for every swap scenario:
    - swapfile on btrfs (incl. @swap subvolume): resume_offset is computed with
      `btrfs inspect-internal map-swapfile -r`;
    - swapfile on ext2/3/4: resume_offset is computed from `filefrag`;
    - an existing swap partition: resume by UUID, no offset.
  It writes RESUME=UUID=<dev> to /etc/initramfs-tools/conf.d/resume and appends
  resume=UUID=<dev> [resume_offset=N] to GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT, then
  update-grub + update-initramfs (the initramfs rebuild now also triggers when
  resume is configured). For a swapfile, resume is only enabled if the offset
  was obtained. Skipped for encrypted root (resuming from encrypted swap needs
  extra setup). Note: hibernation generally does NOT work under VirtualBox;
  test on bare metal.

EFI boot fixes:

  - ESP mount at /target/boot/efi has error checking (check_exit), mkdir -p,
    a pre-unmount of the ESP from any existing mountpoint, and findmnt-based
    verification (df does not list nested mounts).
  - install_grub() verifies the ESP is mounted before grub-install.
  - install_grub() no longer blindly re-mounts a separate /boot in the chroot.
    With EFI + a separate /boot, the ESP-setup phase already mounts /boot (with
    the ESP under it); the redundant chroot remount stacked a second /boot that
    SHADOWED /boot/efi, making grub-install fail with "cannot find EFI
    directory". A findmnt guard now skips the remount when /boot is already
    mounted, while still mounting it for the BIOS / no-ESP path.

Dual logging:

  - A background tail -F mirrors the installer error log to the target disk in
    real time; clean_log() (GUI) sanitizes passwords in both copies; a final
    sync runs at the end of the install.

Changes from v6:
  - Added configure_resume(): hibernation resume= / resume_offset= +
    initramfs RESUME for swapfile (btrfs and ext) and swap-partition installs;
    update-initramfs now also runs when resume is configured.

Changes from v5:
  - install_grub(): findmnt guard around the chroot /boot remount.
  - Swapfile sized to match RAM (whole GiB) on ALL filesystems; chmod before
    mkswap.

Changes from v4:
  - load_btrfs_layout() + btrfs_guess_mount(): layout learned from an on-disk
    manifest (or discovered), not hard-coded; root subvolume derived from it.
  - The format-menu path writes the manifest into the new filesystem.
  - btrfs swapfile created NoCoW and routed into @swap when present.

Compatibility:
  - ext2/ext3/ext4 paths gain RAM-sized swap + hibernation; otherwise unchanged.
  - Encryption (LUKS) is not combined with btrfs, and hibernation is skipped
    for encrypted root.
  - btrfs-progs is required; checked at runtime with a friendly error.

Files patched:
  usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad  (GUI version, 9.6.6)
  usr/bin/refractainstaller      (CLI version, 9.6.6)

Apply with:
  patch -p1 < btrfs-support-for-refractainstaller.patch

